{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.04,0.69,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78531"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26906"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78531"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIntracellular protozoan parasites are significant human pathogens that can persist within host cells for extended periods. One important example is \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E, which can cause severe disease in immunocompromised individuals and during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the life cycle of \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Completes sexual reproduction in humans","Develops only in blood cells","Requires mosquito transmission","Undergoes sexual reproduction in feline intestines","Replicates exclusively in human cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E has a complex life cycle where \u003Cstrong\u003Esexual reproduction occurs in feline intestines\u003C/strong\u003E. Cats are the definitive host, and the only species in which the parasite can complete its sexual cycle, producing oocysts that are shed in faeces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHumans act as an intermediate host and become infected through ingestion of tissue cysts in undercooked meat or oocysts from cat faeces. The parasite then disseminates throughout the body and forms tissue cysts, particularly in skeletal muscle and neural tissue. Here is an example of the parasite in the retina (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReplicates exclusively in human cells\u003C/strong\u003E - \u003Cem\u003ET. gondii\u003C/em\u003E can replicate in many warm-blooded animals, not just humans\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompletes sexual reproduction in humans\u003C/strong\u003E - Humans are intermediate hosts where only asexual reproduction occurs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires mosquito transmission\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike malaria, \u003Cem\u003ET. gondii\u003C/em\u003E does not require an insect vector\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops only in blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E - The parasite forms tissue cysts in muscle and neural tissue, not just blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toxoplasma gondii is an obligate intracellular protozoan that forms tissue cysts in skeletal muscle and neural tissue.","The definitive host for Toxoplasma gondii is the cat family, where sexual reproduction occurs in the intestine.","Humans become infected with Toxoplasma gondii through ingestion of tissue cysts in undercooked meat or oocysts from cat faeces."],"references":["S Al-Malki E. Toxoplasmosis: stages of the protozoan life cycle and risk assessment in humans and animals for an enhanced awareness and an improved socio-economic status. Saudi J Biol Sci. 2021 Jan;28(1):962-969. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7783816/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21453"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21453"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nwkzIHSKD8U7bwvhug7BHV1t5hKLPO.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nwkzIHSKD8U7bwvhug7BHV1t5hKLPO.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":498,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T11:09:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T11:12:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78531"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type"